## GENERATION TIPS

### Best AI Tools for This Style

| Tool | Strengths | Recommended Model |
|------|-----------|------------------|
| **Midjourney** | Best for painterly dark fantasy, atmospheric lighting | v6.1 with `--style raw` |
| **DALL-E 3** | Good detail, consistent compositions | Via ChatGPT Plus |
| **Stable Diffusion** | Free, customizable, LoRA support | SDXL with DreamShaper or Dark Sushi Mix |
| **Leonardo AI** | Good dark fantasy presets | DreamShaper v7 or Dark Fantasy model |
| **Flux** | Excellent prompt adherence | Flux Pro via API |

### Midjourney-Specific Settings

```
/imagine [prompt] --ar 20:7 --style raw --s 250 --c 15 --no text,words,letters,UI
```

For enemy portraits:
```
/imagine [prompt] --ar 1:1 --style raw --s 300 --c 10 --no text,words,letters,background
```

### Post-Processing Workflow

1. Generate at highest resolution available
2. Resize to target dimensions (1600×560 for rooms, 800×800 for enemies)
3. Apply slight vignette darkening at edges (helps blend with game UI)
4. Adjust levels: crush blacks slightly (helps with dark theme)
5. Export as .webp at quality 80-85 (best size/quality ratio)
6. Verify file size under 150KB

### Consistency Tips

- Generate the **chapel** first — use it as your style reference
- For Midjourney, use `--sref [chapel_image_url]` on subsequent room prompts
- Keep the same seed range for similar room types (indoor vs outdoor)
- All interiors should share the same stone texture quality
- All exteriors share the same moonlight quality

---

## HOW THE GAME ENGINE USES THESE

The v6.0 game engine has been updated with:

1. **`ROOM_IMAGES` config** — maps each roomId to its image filename
2. **`ENEMY_IMAGES` config** — maps enemy types to portrait filenames
3. **Hybrid rendering** — if image exists, shows it as background with SVG knight overlay; if missing, falls back to full SVG (backwards compatible)
4. **Lazy loading** — images preload on adjacent rooms for smooth transitions
5. **Special scenes** — golden armor, death, and victory use dedicated images

The game works **with or without** the images. SVG art is always the fallback. You can add images one at a time — each room upgrades independently.
